stem:
Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] arr = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
System.out.println(arr[0] + arr[arr.length - 1]);
```

The following code is intended to print every element of array `a`, but it contains a bug. What will happen when the code runs?

```java
int[] a = {3, 1, 4, 1, 5};
for (int i = 0; i <= a.length; i++) {
    System.out.print(a[i] + " ");
}
```

Determine the value of `vals[0]` after the following code executes:

```java
int[] vals = {2, 4, 6, 8};
for (int v : vals) {
    v = v * 2;
}
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] data = {5, 3, 8, 2};
int result = 0;
for (int i = 1; i < data.length; i++) {
    result += data[i];
}
System.out.println(result);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] a = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
for (int i = 0; i < a.length - 1; i++) {
    a[i + 1] = a[i + 1] + a[i];
}
System.out.println(a[4]);
```

The following method is intended to return `true` if any element of the array is negative, and `false` otherwise. Which of the following best describes the bug?

```java
public static boolean hasNegative(int[] arr) {
    for (int v : arr) {
        if (v < 0)
            return true;
        else
            return false;
    }
    return false;
}
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] a = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
int i = 0, j = a.length - 1;
while (i < j) {
    int temp = a[i];
    a[i] = a[j];
    a[j] = temp;
    i++;
    j--;
}
System.out.println(a[0] + " " + a[2] + " " + a[4]);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] nums = {3, 7, 1, 5, 2};
System.out.println(nums[nums.length - 2]);
```

Which of the following best describes the result of attempting to compile and run the code below?

```java
int[] scores = {90, 85, 78};
int sum = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < scores.length(); i++)
{
    sum += scores[i];
}
System.out.println(sum);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] a = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
a[2] = a[1] + a[3];
a[0] = a[2] - a[4];
System.out.println(a[0] + " " + a[2]);
```

What is printed by the following code?

```java
int[] nums = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
for (int val : nums)
{
    val = val * 2;
}
System.out.println(nums[0] + " " + nums[4]);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] nums = {3, 7, 1, 9, 4};
System.out.println(nums[nums.length - 2]);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] values = {5, 10, 15};
for (int v : values) {
    v = v + 1;
}
System.out.println(values[1]);
```

Determine the value printed by the following code:

```java
int[] data = new int[4];
data[0] = 7;
data[3] = 2;
System.out.println(data[1] + data[2]);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] a = {2, 4, 6, 8};
int result = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < a.length; i += 2) {
    result += a[i];
}
System.out.println(result);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int[] nums = new int[4];
nums[1] = 3;
nums[3] = nums.length + nums[1];
System.out.print(nums[0] + " " + nums[2] + " " + nums[3]);
```

Consider the following code segment:

```java
int[] vals = {2, 4, 6};
for (int i = 0; i <= vals.length; i++)
{
    System.out.print(vals[i] + " ");
}
```

Which replacement for the loop header prevents an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` and prints every element of `vals`?
